<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much should I save in my emergency fund?", answer: "Financial experts generally recommend saving 3 to 9 months of essential living expenses. If you have a stable job with predictable income, 3 months may be sufficient. If you are self-employed, work in a volatile industry, or have a single income household, 6 to 9 months provides a larger safety net. The right amount depends on your personal risk factors and comfort level." },
  { question: "What counts as monthly expenses for an emergency fund?", answer: "Include all essential monthly expenses: rent or mortgage, utilities, groceries, insurance premiums, minimum debt payments, transportation costs, and any other bills you cannot avoid. Do not include discretionary spending like dining out or entertainment, since you would cut those in a true emergency." },
  { question: "Where should I keep my emergency fund?", answer: "Keep your emergency fund in a high-yield savings account that is easily accessible but separate from your everyday checking account. This separation helps prevent accidental spending while keeping the money liquid for true emergencies. Money market accounts and short-term CDs are also good options, though CDs may have early withdrawal penalties." },
  { question: "Should I invest my emergency fund?", answer: "No, your emergency fund should not be invested in stocks, bonds, or other volatile assets. The purpose of an emergency fund is immediate access to cash when unexpected expenses arise. Investments can lose value at the worst possible time, such as during a recession when job losses are more likely. A high-yield savings account provides modest returns while keeping your money safe and accessible." },
